Loops in C 
Loops are control structures used to repeat a block of code multiple times as long as a specified condition remains true.
1. For Loop Best used when you know exactly how many times the loop should execute.Syntax: for (initialization; condition; increment/decrement) { ... }Key Detail: The three components inside the for statement must be separated by semicolons (;).Execution Workflow:Initialization: Runs once (e.g., int i = 0;).Condition Check: If true (e.g., i < 5), the block executes.Increment/Decrement: Updates the iterator (e.g., i++) after the block code executes, then checks the condition again.Example: Prints "Hello" 5 times (for $i = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4$).
2. While Loop Best used when the number of iterations is not known beforehand, relying strictly on a condition.Syntax: while (condition) { ... }Execution Workflow:Checks the condition first. If true, it enters the loop body.You must manually include an increment/decrement step inside the block (e.g., i++;) to modify the iterator, otherwise, it creates an infinite loop.Example: Checks i < 5, prints "Hello", increments i, and repeats.
3. Do-While Loop An exit-controlled loop that guarantees execution at least once, regardless of whether the condition is initially true or false.
Syntax:C do {
    // block of code
} while (condition); // Note the trailing semicolon here
